Africa
------
[1] Sierra Leone (ex Guinea)
Date: Sun 13 Jul 2015
Source: Kissi Kama Kailahun District State House Communications Unit [abridged & edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.sierraexpressmedia.com/?author=10#sthash.M7dJE1FA.dp


The Kailahun District Health Management Team has reported suspected imported cases of measles from Guinea to the Kissi Kama Chiefdom in the Kailahun district [Sierra Leone]. The Surveillance Report states that 2 samples were collected from 2 children from Kunduma, Kama Chiefdom and who were seen and treated at the Dia Community Health Centre. 1 child [SK] exhibited the typical prodromal stage with coryza and weakness. According to the surveillance report 10 children are suspected to have measles.

Meanwhile, the Kailahun District Health Management Team on Saturday 4 Jul 2015 mounted community sensitization campaign in all 8 villages in the chiefdom with the Ring Vaccination of the leftover buffer stock from the past measles campaign.

Earlier on 10 Jul 2015 it was reported that: Suspected Measles Cases had been reported in Kailahun District (http://www.premiermedia.sl/content/suspected-measles-cases-reported-kailahun-district}. "The Kailahun District Health Management Team had reported suspected imported cases of Measles from Guinea to the Kissi Kama Chiefdom in the Kailahun District Community Health Centre.

The Ministry of Health and Sanitation in collaboration with UNICEF, the World Health Organization (WHO) and the U.S. Centre for Disease Control early in June conducted a six-day nationwide measles and polio vaccination campaign.

Children 9-59 months of age were targeted, while for the polio immunization children 0-59 months were also targeted.

Dr Marke said 1st-time pregnant women will also receive a referral slip to collect Long Lasting Insecticide Nets (LLIN). He called on parents to take their children for vaccination during the campaign. "This vaccination has nothing to do with Ebola," he said. "All children under 5 years should be vaccinated against polio regardless of the number of previous polio vaccinia," he said.

The measles campaign intended achieving 95 percent coverage during the vaccination campaign. He said plans are afoot to reach hard-to-reach communities, including riverine communities. The measles campaign came following report of 5 confirmed measles cases in Kono District out of 31 suspected cases.

According to a recent study, 864 children in Sierra Leone have been suspected of being affected with measles. The largest number of suspected measles cases during the assessment period was identified in the Western Area Urban with 297 cases, followed by Koinadugu with 159 cases, and Bo with 124 cases. 92 percent of suspected measles cases identified during the assessment were children under 5. Infants accounted for 29 percent of cases and children 1-4 years accounted for another 63 percent.

